Dr Shivakumar swamiji has been shifted to the Siddaganga mutt from hospital at 3:45 am. Seer is being treated at a room of the old mutt. Swamiji has not been keeping well from the past several weeks. The seer is suffering from lung infection.
Seer's personal doctor Paramesh said that Dr Shivakumara swamiji has been shifted to the mutt on his orders.
Dr Paramesh also said that treatment will continue at the mutt and infection has reduced and nutritional treatment will be given to him.
Dr Paramesh also said that there is no need to panic and asked devotees to not to visit the mutt as seer is being treated for the infection.
Security too has been heightened around the Siddaganga mutt.

Jio Diwali Offer 2019 Phone At Rs 699

ಜಿಯೋ ಫೋನ್ ಖರೀದಿ ಮಾಡಬೇಕು ಎಂದು ಅಂದು ಕೊಂಡವರಿಗೆ ಇಲ್ಲಿದೆ ಒಂದು ಸದಾವಕಾಶ!

#JioPhone, the affordable smart feature phone supporting 4G LTE, will be available for purchase with a special price of Rs. #699RS during this festive season, Reliance Jio announced through a press statement on Tuesday. The phone was launched at Rs. 1,500 back in July 2017, though it received an exchange offer last month that brought its price down to effectively Rs. 501. However, the telco has now announced that the new discounted price, which is available under the "#JioPhoneDiwali2019" offer, will be applicable without any "special conditions" or exchange discounts.

Jio Phone price in India, special offers:
as per the Jio Phone Diwali 2019 offer, the Jio Phone price in India will be set at Rs. 699. Reliance Jio is also committed to offering data benefits worth Rs. 700 for customers recharging the Jio Phone. To avail additional data, customers will need to make the first seven recharges for which the telco will add additional Rs. 99 worth of data. Reliance Jio has confirmed to Gadgets 360 that the new offer will be applicable starting October 4.

Jio Phone Specifications:
The KaiOS-based Jio Phone features a 2.4-inch display and is powered by a 1.2GHz dual-core processor, coupled with 512MB of RAM. The phone has 4GB of internal storage along with microSD card support (up to 128GB) and includes Wi-Fi connectivity as well as a 2,000mAh battery.

FLORENCE, Ky. (WKRC) - Another local food service worker tested positive for hepatitis A, but health officials say the risk of exposure to patrons is considered to be low.

An employee at Lee's Famous Recipe on Burlington Pike in Florence has been diagnosed. The health department says the person worked there on Aug. 25th and 26 during a period of time when they were infectious.

Officials say the restaurant is taking steps to disinfect any areas that may have been contaminated.

This is the third time in the past month a food service worker has been diagnosed with hepatitis A.
title: Florence food service worker diagnosed with hepatitis A

description:
CINCINNATI (WKRC) - If you didn't quite meet your summer shape up goals, it's not too late.

A plateau is generally at least three to seven weeks where workout or weight loss seems to stop, but you can seek some help pushing past the plateau.

There is probably no one that gets asked more about pushing through a plateau than Dave Rechtin. He's an athletic trainer at  G&G Fitness Equipment.

He says if the treadmill is your traditional workout and you can't seem to move the scale or shrink a size, mixing it up might matter.

"If you're a treadmill person, it's really almost about moving on to anything else that's going to work different muscle groups, work them differently. Rowers are really popular nowadays," Rechtin said.

Rowers use the whole body, including your core. It also gives you a total body workout for aerobic capacity and calorie burning. The new, hot thing, however, is the adaptive motion trainer.

"It's a great workout. You can never get the same workout twice on it," Rechtin said.

In addition to that, however, Rechtin points out that there are a few other things you have to do on top of the aerobic activity to get an all-encompassing, good fitness plan that really can help you push past the plateau.

The first is some form of strength training. Adaptable weights can help build muscle, and a fit muscle burns more calories when you are at rest.

If weights aren't your thing, there's something called a vibration plate. It's a platform for strength that also helps balance.

Finally, flexibility can help you push past a plateau by lowering pain and injury risk. So a simple stretching machine is a great way to get fit while you sit.

The machines at G&G Fitness Equipment start as low as about $500 dollars.
title: Mixing up your workout plan could help you push past the weight-loss plateau

description:
CINCINNATI (WKRC) - A man charged in a Mt. Airy murder admits to being at the scene but denies pulling the trigger. Raymere Buck was arraigned Wednesday.

Buck is charged with aggravated murder for the shooting death of Jaylyn McCoy on Aug. 21 on Hawaiian Terrace during a robbery attempt. A second person was also shot.

Buck's attorney says he was there but someone Buck knows only as "P" was the person who was going to rob McCoy. The attorney says the other shooting victim started firing shots and that's when Buck took off.

Assistant prosecutor David Wood requested a high bond, noting Buck was already on probation at the time of the shooting.

Judge Tyrone Yates ordered Buck held on one million dollars bond.
title: Mt. Airy murder suspect says he didn't pull the trigger

description:
CINCINNATI (WKRC) - There are a few foods with an important vitamin could help your hair, but you might be missing it in your diet.

It's that time of year where you may be trying to repair your hair after months of summer swimming, sunshine and chlorine damage. A study from the National Institutes of Health says a vitamin might make a difference.

Stylist Sara Ruf says including topical moisturizing treatments and getting a haircut can help your hair's health, but the study says adding vitamin D might also help.

Researchers found that women with thinning hair had nearly five times lower blood levels of vitamin D compared to than those with fuller hair.

You can take vitamin D as a supplement. Generally, vitamin D3 is recommended for best absorption. You can also get it in some foods known to be good for healthy hair. These include salmon, tuna, milk and eggs.

Since a nutrient or vitamin only helps a problem if you have a deficiency of it, it's suggested you ask your doctor to test your vitamin D levels if you notice your hair is thinning.
title: Vitamin D could help you have healthier, shinier hair

description:
CINCINNATI (WKRC) - A new study has important information for new mothers about diet and brain health.

Researchers in this study looked at the impact of sugar intake  early in life, especially during pregnancy.

While we've known sugar can play a role in weight gain and heart health, researchers in the American Journal of Preventive Medicine in this study wanted to find out how it might impact a child's brain function.

Every pregnancy and every body is different, but researchers say it's likely the kind of natural sugar found in fruits and fruit juices are good for mother and baby. However, high levels of added sugar in sweetened beverages may be a problem.

The study looked at data from more than 1,000  pairs of mothers and children. Researchers found that women who had high sugar diets, especially those who drank a lot of soda during pregnancy, were more likely to have children with poorer cognitive skills.

This can include everything from how verbal a child may or may not be to their problem-solving skills to even what they can remember or recall. The same was true for young children who consumed greater amounts of sugar early in life.

Eating fruit with natural sugar, however, was associated with greater visual motor abilities and verbal intelligence. Right now, it's recommended that children under the age of 2 have no added sugar. Children 2 or older should have no more than 25 grams, or six teaspoons, of added sugar a day. Natural sugar, like that found in fresh fruit,  does not count against the daily limit.

Researchers also looked at diet soda in this study. It also appeared to be linked to cognition concerns.

If you want to check for lower-sugar foods, look on the ingredient list and see if it's in the first three ingredients.
title: High sugar intake during pregnancy linked to poorer cognitive abilities in children

Palestinian families held an Ifatr dinner on the rubble of a building reportedly destroyed by Israeli strikes, in Gaza City on Saturday.

The Iftar dinner marks the end of the daily period of fasting for Muslims during the holy month of Ramadan.

"The message today is that we are making collective Iftar, fast breaking, on the rubble of this tower to confirm that this barbarous assault will not let the Palestinian people concede his right", one resident said.

The building, reportedly known as Qamar tower, consisted of 12 floors. The Iftar meal reportedly marked the first time that the families dined on the building's rubble.

description:
Methane is a powerful greenhouse gas, with a global warming potential over 80 times more powerful than carbon dioxide. The oil and gas sector is the largest industrial source of methane emissions, much of it in the form of leaks, which can be seen using special thermal cameras. Preventing wasted gases and other forms of methane emissions is an effective way of fighting rapid climate change.

Produced by UN Environment.

Share your voice to #BeatAirPollution, take the mask challenge: https://www.worldenvironmentday.global/get-involved/world-environment-day-mask-challenge

title: Invisible Emissions - High tech cameras reveal methane leaks

description:
Security Council extends mandate of African Union Mission in Somalia and authorizes troop reduction, unanimously adopting resolution 2472 (2019) at 8537th meeting.

The Security Council today (31 May) unanimously voted to extend the mandate of the AU Mission in Somalia (AMISOM) for another year. Somali Ambassador Mohamed Rabi Yusuf said, “we are cognizant that AMISOM cannot stay in Somalia forever,” but stressed that “any planned drawdown must be done after thoroughly assessing the conditions on the ground.”

Full meeting is available on UN WebTV: http://webtv.un.org/watch/security-council-the-situation-in-somalia-8537th-meeting/6043283520001/

description:
Briefing by Farhan Haq, Deputy Spokesperson for the President of the Secretary-General Antonio Guterres.

Highlights:
- Secretary-General travels
- Deputy Secretary-General travels
- Mozambique
- Madagascar
- Libya
- Yemen
- No Tobacco Day
- No Plastic
- Correction

SG TRAVELS
The Secretary-General will travel on 5 June to St. Petersburg in the Russian Federation, where he will participate in the St. Petersburg International Economic Forum, which begins in that city on the following day.
The forum will be a venue where the Secretary-General can talk to leaders about implementing the Sustainable Development Goals.  The theme of this year’s forum is “Creating a Sustainable Development Agenda”.
The Secretary-General will travel back to New York on 8 June.

DSG TRAVELS
This evening, the Deputy Secretary-General, Amina Mohammed, will depart New York for London to attend the Our Shared Humanity meetings of the United Nations Association-UK and Chatham House. Those meetings will take place on 3 and 4 June.
The Deputy Secretary-General will also be meeting with senior officials and other stakeholders on advancing the Sustainable Development Goals while in London.

MOZAMBIQUE
The United Nations is supporting the Government of Mozambique, which is convening a pledging conference for recovery and reconstruction in the wake of the devastation caused by Tropical Cyclones Idai and Kenneth.
Two strong tropical cyclones hit Mozambique and the Southern Africa region in the same season for the first time in recorded history.
The pledging conference, which began today, is bringing together 500 representatives from governments, international organizations, development partners, the private sector and civil society.
The Secretary-General will have a message for the conference tomorrow in which he will reiterate his appeal to the generosity of the international community, noting that this is the moment to translate into concrete gestures our solidarity with Mozambique. He will also stress how the cyclones warn us about the urgency of tackling climate change.

Full Highlights: https://www.un.org/sg/en/content/noon-briefing-highlight?date%5Bvalue%5D%5Bdate%5D=31%20May%202019

description:
Crime is on the rise at Walmarts across the country. Why is this happening? Cenk Uygur and Ana Kasparian, hosts of The Young Turks, break it down. Tell us what you think in the comment section below. http://tytnetwork.com/join

"It’s not unusual for the department to send a van to transport all the criminals Ross arrests at this Walmart. The call log on the store stretches 126 pages, documenting more than 5,000 trips over the past five years. Last year police were called to the store and three other Tulsa Walmarts just under 2,000 times. By comparison, they were called to the city’s four Target stores about 300 times. Most of the calls to the northeast Supercenter were for shoplifting, but there’s no shortage of more serious crimes, including five armed robberies so far this year, a murder suspect who killed himself with a gunshot to the head in the parking lot last year, and, in 2014, a group of men who got into a parking lot shootout that killed one and seriously injured two others.

Police reports from dozens of stores suggest the number of petty crimes committed on Walmart properties nationwide this year will be in the hundreds of thousands. But people dashing out the door with merchandise is the least troubling part of Walmart’s crime problem. More than 200 violent crimes, including attempted kidnappings and multiple stabbings, shootings, and murders, have occurred at the nation’s 4,500 Walmarts this year, or about one a day, according to an analysis of media reports.”*

Read more here: https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2016-walmart-crime/

description:
A Florida college student recently murdered a couple and began eating their faces. Police say he shrugged off multiple tasers and a police dog before being apprehended alive. Cenk Uygur and Ana Kasparian, hosts of The Young Turks, break it down. Tell us what you think in the comment section below. http://tytnetwork.com/join

"Something made a young man go mad.

He viciously stabbed a married couple twice his age, plus a neighbor who tried to intervene, deputies said. They found him crouched over the bleeding body of the man, biting chunks of his face off.

Martin County Sheriff William Snyder told reporters his deputies found the suspect late Monday in the driveway of a Tequesta home. Officers shot their stun guns at the 19-year-old multiple times to no avail. Even a police dog couldn’t get the man to release his victim.

Finally, three to four cops were able to wrench the suspect off the dead man. The man was “making animal noises,” and “grunting and growling” as officers yanked him away.

Inside the garage they found his wife, also stabbed to death. Multiple “weapons of opportunity” were used to beat, slash and attack the couple, including a switchblade the suspect was known to carry. Officials said it looked like the husband tried to fight back.”*

description:
Egypt has state news where the government directly directly hires and controls the message. They have decided to suspend several female anchors until they lose sufficient weight. Cenk Uygur and Ana Kasparian, hosts of The Young Turks, break it down. Tell us what you think in the comment section below. http://tytnetwork.com/join

"The state TV broadcaster in Egypt has sparked outrage after reportedly suspending eight of its female anchors and instructing them to diet. The Egyptian Radio and Television Union (ERTU) has given the women a month to lose weight before they can resume their on-air roles with an “appropriate appearance,” according to the Al-Yawm al-Sabi website.

ERTU’s director, Safaa Hegazy, is a former TV anchor herself. The broadcaster is standing by the decision, but says the women’s pay and benefits will not be docked while they are suspended from appearing on the air. Opinions were divided on social media, with some calling the women “bakabouzas” (an Egyptian term for overweight females) and praising Hegazy’s strong decision. The Women’s Center for Guidance and Legal Awareness said the move “violates the constitution.””*

Read more here: http://nytlive.nytimes.com/womenintheworld/2016/08/17/broadcaster-suspends-8-women-tv-anchors-and-orders-them-to-lose-weight/

ILLINOIS: Heavy rainfall was once again the story across the Midwest on Wednesday evening when up to 2" of rain fell in just an hour in Macomb, IL leading to flash flooding of many area streets. Vehicles are seen having a difficult time getting around in the at times knee deep water. This is part of a larger weather system that is producing record heat, heavy snow, and flash flooding across much of the nation. Some of the local area has seen 8" or more of rain in the last week and more is expected.

US President Donald Trump has said he expects a "powerful" trade deal with the UK to be completed "very quickly".
Speaking at the G20 summit in Hamburg, he said he would go to London. Asked when, he said: "We'll work that out".
The US president is holding talks with UK Prime Minister Theresa May to discuss a post-Brexit trade deal.
It is one of a series of one-to-one meetings with world leaders which will also see Mrs May hold trade talks with Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe.
Ahead of their meeting, Mr Trump hailed the "very special relationship" he had developed with Mrs May.

So while the statement at the O.A.S. by Belize was sanctioned, according to DPM Faber, Belize will not support any type of intervention or interference from any international superpower, such as the U.S.  He says that Venezuela has the right to self-determination without political, economic or military interference from other world states.
title: Belize Does Not Support U.S. Interference in Venezuela

description:
For the latest news across Belize, visit:
http://edition.channel5belize.com/

On January twenty-sixth, the United Democratic Party’s National Party Council decided that its leadership convention will be held in February 2020. Up to date, there are only two known candidates who have made their political aspirations public. There is Deputy Party Leader Patrick Faber as well as John Saldivar, the area representative for Belmopan and Minister of National Security. Recently, Foreign Minister Wilfred Elrington told News Five that the position of leadership is not reserved for any special person and that he won’t rule out the possibility of contesting the leadership position. We asked Minister Faber about it today.
title: U.D.P. Leadership Convention Set for February 2020

description:
For the latest news across Belize, visit:
http://edition.channel5belize.com/

While we had the minister, we asked him about another statement from cabinet colleague Elrington in an interview with this station. When asked to respond to the P.U.P.’s umpteenth call for his removal, Elrington said that the demand was futile. According to Elrington, people very close to the Prime Minister and in the U.D.P. camp have called for his removal since 2008. According to Faber, that is not the way he sees it.
title: Minister Faber Expresses Confidence in FM Elrington

description:
For the latest news across Belize, visit:
http://edition.channel5belize.com/

In the next few days, a group of attorneys are set to file a constitutional challenge in the Supreme Court. The group will be challenging the validity of the Compromis, signed between Belize and Guatemala to end negotiations and take the territorial dispute between both countries to the International Court of Justice for final resolution. On December eighth, 2008 Belize’s Minister of Foreign Affairs Wilfred Elrington and then Guatemalan Foreign Minister, Haroldo Rodas, as well as O.A.S. Secretary General Jose Miguel Insulza, signed on to the special agreement at the O.A.S. Headquarters in Washington. Back then, like now, there is outcry over the agreement which had the support from both major political parties. Attorney Richard “Dickie” Bradley says that the Executive did not have the legal authority to sign the binding document without parliamentary approval.
title: A Challenge to the Validity of the Compromis Soon to be Filed

description:
For the latest news across Belize, visit:
http://edition.channel5belize.com/

The challenge comes less than two months before the April tenth referendum when voters are to decide on whether or not to take the claim to the I.C.J.  It’s been eleven years since the agreement was signed, the document went through an amendment and the referendum delinked with Guatemala. Despite a low turnout, Guatemala held its referendum in 2018 and voted to go to the I.C.J.  Bradley, who is known to oppose going to the I.C.J., explains his concerns with the Compromis and not knowing the extent of the Guatemalan claim.
title: Should Belize Go to the I.C.J., Not Knowing the Extent of Guatemalan Claim?

The police shooting of unarmed Florida teenager Trayvon Martin created a national outcry. It led to the Black Lives Matter movement and the backlash against it. Trayvon Martin's father, Tracy Martin, along with filmmakers Jenner Furst and Julia Willoughby Nason, join "CBS This Morning" to discuss how so much has changed in the nation since then, but so much has remained the same. description: South African President, Cyril Ramaphosa is hosting Nigeria’s President Muhammdu Buhari who is on a three day state visit to South Africa. The state visit comes against a backdrop of xenophobic violence that sent shivers down the spine of the continent. The two countries look to strengthen trade ties in the areas of science, technology, transport, agriculture, tourism and culture.

description: The global oil space is facing new tensions after a recent drone attack on Saudi Arabia’s Aramco installations impacted the output of the world’s top oil producer. As the oil market rebalances – to explore Nigeria’s place in the global oil market and more, Tunde Afolabi, Chairman and CEO of AMNI International Petroleum Development Company and President of the Petroleum Club of Lagos joins CNBC Africa's Esther Awoniyi for more.
tags: Beyond Markets,West Africa,Africa,emerging markets,Nigeria,PRG_beyond_021019_P1,Saudi Arabia,Aramco installations,global oil space,drone attack,Tunde Afolabi,AMNI International Petroleum Development Company,Petroleum Club of Lagos
title: Nigeria’s contemporary stance in the global oil market

description: One of the big names in world aviation opens up on the airline business. On Captains of Industry Emirates Airline legend Tim Clark gives a candid account of his hopes and fears for business in the skies over the Middle East and Africa.
tags: Captains of Industry,Leadership,entrepreneurship,CNBC Africa,Africa,Tim Clark,Emirates airline
title: Captains of Industry: One-on-one with Tim Clark on Emirates airlines expansion plans

description: As Nigeria celebrates its Independence Day, 59 years has been quite a journey since the breakaway from colonial rule. Nigeria is currently in its fourth Republic and democracy has taken a much stronger hold since 1999. To discuss how Nigeria plans to forge ahead – Chamberlain Peterside; CEO of Xcellon Capital Advisory, Andrew Nevin; Partner and Chief Economist at PwC Nigeria, and Ajuri Ngelale; Senior Special Assistant to President Muhammadu Buhari on Public Affairs all join CNBC Africa's Kenneth Igbomor for more.
tags: PRG_nigerDAY_011019_P1,Nigeria,Independence Day,colonial rule,democracy,Chamberlain Peterside,Xcellon Capital Advisory,Andrew Nevin,PwC Nigeria,PricewaterhouseCoopers,Ajuri Ngelale,Muhammadu Buhari,Public Affairs,Forging Ahead
title: Nigeria turns 59: What’s been accomplished and what still needs to be done

description:
The UK High Court has ruled in favour of India and dismissed Pakistan's claim over funds belonging to the late 7th Nizam of Hyderabad at the time of Partition in 1947 and now worth around 35 million pounds. The ruling marks an important conclusion to the over 70-year-long legal dispute which also witnessed the Indian government, the descendants of the 7th Nizam and the administrator of his estate burying their differences and entering into a confidential settlement agreement last year, which meant the case was effectively an India-Pakistan clash in the British courts. Watch the full story in Khoj Khabar with Peenaz Tyagi.

description:
The Mumbai police has arrested Housing Development and Infrastructure Limited (HDIL) directors Rakesh and Sarang Wadhawan in connection with the Punjab and Maharashtra Co-operative (PMC) Bank scam. The police have also frozen their assets. According to the FIR registered against them, they had taken a loan worth Rs 3,337 crore from the PMC bank which later turned into NPA. Few of the senior bank officials, including directors of the PMC bank were also involved in the fraud.

The parties in the fray are the ruling Telugu Desam Party seeking a re-election, Y.S. Jaganmohan Reddy’s YSR Congress, and actor-turned-politician Pawan Kalyan’s Jana Sena — the new entrant.
Voting for 175 Assembly seats and 25 Parliamentary seats in Andhra Pradesh is being held simultaneously in a single-phase election on Thursday. It is essentially a three-cornered fight in the State — the ruling Telugu Desam Party seeking a re-election, Y.S. Jaganmohan Reddy’s YSR Congress emerging as a strong contender, and actor-turned-politician Pawan Kalyan’s Jana Sena the new entrant.

There are also the national parties the BJP and Congress contesting sans any alliance with the regional parties.
